Abstract

Blockade of the renin-angiotensin system with angiotensin II receptor blockers ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) provides blood pressure ({{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }})-independent effects throughout the cardiovascular (CV) continuum. In the landmark ongoing {{ drug.name }} alone and in combination with ramipril global endpoint trial ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), {{ drug.name }} reduced CV events in patients at high CV risk, similar to the angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor, ramipril. This reduction in CV events is a consequence of non-{{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} effects on disease pathophysiology which have been demonstrated in preclinical and clinical studies. For example, {{ drug.name }} significantly reduces markers of inflammation, such as interleukin-6 and C-reactive protein, and improves markers of vascular function, such as pulse wave velocity. Both these are associated with target organ damage. {{ drug.name }} also has numerous potentially beneficial metabolic effects in preclinical studies. {{ drug.name }} reduces markers of renal disease and its progression, left ventricular hypertrophy, and the risk of primary or secondary atrial fibrillation. Many of these effects are shared with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitors. However, several studies indicate differential effects between {{ drug.name }} and other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. These differences probably reflect {{ drug.name }}’s distinct pharmacologic profile, including the longest plasma half-life, high receptor-binding affinity, and highest lipophilicity of the class. These differences suggest that the results of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} do not necessarily extrapolate to other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}.

1. Introduction

The renin-angiotensin system ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), and most importantly angiotensin II, is central to the pathogenesis of a variety of clinical conditions along the cardiovascular (CV) continuum, from risk factors such as hypertension and diabetes, to atherosclerosis and left ventricular hypertrophy ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), and ultimately to myocardial infarction (MI), stroke, and heart failure (Figure 1). Blockade of the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} can be achieved at different levels of the system with renin inhibitors, angiotensin-converting enzyme ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) inhibitors, or angiotensin II receptor blockers ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}). {{ drug.molecular_formula }} differ from other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockers in that they block the action of angiotensin II at the angiotensin AT1 receptor but allow continued activation of other receptors—most notably, the angiotensin AT2receptor. There is little evidence as yet for event-reducing CV effects of renin inhibitors, beyond blood pressure ({{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}) reduction, but some {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitors and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} are now proven to reduce the risk of CV disease in a variety of at-risk patient types, including hypertensive patients, patients with atherosclerosis, {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, coronary heart disease, heart failure, or diabetic patients with target organ damage, for example, diabetic nephropathy.

Figure 1: The cardiovascular continuum.

In the ongoing {{ drug.name }} alone and in combination with Ramipril global endpoint trial ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), {{ drug.name }} was the first {{ drug.molecular_formula }} demonstrated to prevent CV events in patients at high CV risk, similar to the risk reduction with ramipril; importantly, {{ drug.name }} was better tolerated than ramipril. {{ drug.name }} is the only {{ drug.molecular_formula }} indicated for the reduction of CV morbidity in patients with manifest atherothrombotic CV disease (history of coronary heart disease, stroke, or peripheral arterial disease) or type 2 diabetes mellitus with documented target organ damage. Agents within the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} drug class exhibit different pharmacologic profiles. {{ drug.name }} has a relatively long dissociation half-life from the AT1 receptor and a long plasma half-life (24 h) compared with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, thus providing sustained {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} control over the whole dosing interval. {{ drug.name }} has a high binding affinity for the AT1 receptor compared with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, and is highly lipophilic with the greatest volume of distribution. These pharmacologic properties of {{ drug.name }} versus other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} may translate into differences in clinical outcomes. Although there have been limited comparative clinical studies of CV outcomes with {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, there have been a number of studies examining pathophysiologic and intermediate end points. These could shed light on the effects of {{ drug.name }} seen in {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, and in particular whether these effects can be translated into other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}.

This review aims to assess the effects of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} on CV disease pathophysiologies along the CV continuum. The particular focus will be on {{ drug.name }}, to investigate the evidence for a direct effect of this agent on CV disease processes that may have contributed to the effects on CV outcomes seen in {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. The bulk of research on {{ drug.name }} has investigated aspects of CV disease related to inflammation, vascular function, metabolic status, and target organ damage, such as renal disease and CV and cerebrovascular changes. Within each section, this review will briefly consider the evidence for {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in general, before examining the preclinical and clinical evidence on {{ drug.name }}, including comparative studies versus other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} where they exist. Suitable papers were identified by searching {{ drug.molecular_formula }} for studies on {{ drug.molecular_formula }} that included keywords related to the topics under consideration.

2. Inflammation

Inflammation is involved in the pathogenesis and continuation of atherosclerosis and contributes to the development of hypertension and its complications. Angiotensin II acts as a proinflammatory cytokine, inducing inflammation through the upregulation of reactive oxygen species, adhesion molecules, and inflammatory cytokines. Therefore, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibition has the potential to reduce inflammation in patients at risk of CV disease, and this is supported by several in vitro studies. For example, losartan (as well as captopril or amlodipine, but not atenolol or hydrochlorothiazide ({{ drug.molecular_formula }})) produced marked anti-inflammatory effects at clinically relevant serum concentrations, as shown by interleukin-1 beta (IL-1β) secretion by polymorphonuclear leukocytes from patients with essential hypertension.

Studies in humans have confirmed these effects. In two studies of hypertensive patients with or without diabetes, valsartan or candesartan for 6 months decreased serum high-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-{{ drug.molecular_formula }}) and IL-6. In another study of high-risk hypertensive diabetic patients with high baseline IL-6 (>2.0 ng/L; 𝑛 = 5 4), valsartan {{ drug.strength }} for 16 weeks significantly reduced IL-6 (a decrease from 3.5 to 2.4 with valsartan {{ drug.strength }} versus an increase from 3.2 to 3.5 with placebo, 𝑃 = 0 . 0 3 5). In a small study of hypertensive patients with coronary artery disease, for 3 months both irbesartan and enalapril significantly reduced serum metalloprotease 9 protein (𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 1 and 𝑃 < 0 . 0 5, resp.), but only irbesartan reduced hs-{{ drug.molecular_formula }} and IL-6 (both 𝑃 < 0 . 0 1 versus baseline). Another study has shown that olmesartan on a background of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} significantly reduced vascular microinflammation, as shown by serum hs-{{ drug.molecular_formula }} (–15.1%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 5), hs-tumor necrosis factor ({{ drug.molecular_formula }})α (–8.9%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 2), IL-6 (–14.0%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 5), and monocyte chemotactic protein-1 ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}-1) (–6.5%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 1) versus placebo.

{{ drug.name }} has also been shown in animal models to reduce the levels of several markers of inflammation, such as interleukins and TNFα. In a rat model, {{ drug.name }} protected against experimental autoimmune myocarditis, partly by suppressing inflammatory cytokines and oxidative stress. In this model, compared with vehicle-treated rats, {{ drug.name }} decreased myocardial expression of inflammatory cytokines (such as IL-6 and TNFα), nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) oxidase subunits, and decreased endoplasmic reticulum stress markers. In an obese mouse model, {{ drug.name }} or captopril reduced chemically induced colon carcinogenesis by attenuating chronic inflammation and reducing oxidative stress in obese mice. This was shown by decreased expression of TNFα messenger ribonucleic acid (mRNA) in the colonic mucosa and significantly reduced levels of a marker of oxidative damage to deoxyribonucleic acid compared with a control group.

There is some evidence that {{ drug.name }} provides greater anti-inflammatory effects than other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockers. In a mouse model, {{ drug.name }} reduced atherosclerotic lesion progression and reduced the expression of inflammatory factors to a greater extent than ramipril. In vitro, {{ drug.name }} (unlike losartan or its active metabolites {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-3174 and {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-3179) reduced endothelial inflammation and oxidative cell damage in human umbilical vein endothelial cells.

Consistent with these preclinical studies, {{ drug.name }} has shown differential effects in human subjects compared with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. In hypertensive patients with significant coronary artery stenosis, 8-month treatment with {{ drug.name }} (but not valsartan) significantly decreased IL-6 and TNFα as well as late lumen loss (0 . 1 ± 0 . 4 versus 0 . 3 ± 0 . 5 mm; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 1). In metabolic syndrome patients, switching from valsartan to {{ drug.name }} for 12 weeks significantly reduced hs-{{ drug.molecular_formula }} (0.77 versus 0.{{ drug.strength }}/L; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 2 2) as well as microalbuminuria (28.1 versus 18.{{ drug.strength }}/g·Cr; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 1). In a small study, {{ drug.name }} had a more potent antioxidative effect than losartan through its ability to enhance superoxide dismutase activity in type 2 diabetic patients with microalbuminuria. Of note is that oxidative stress induced by excessive superoxide plays a central role in the pathogenesis of diabetic nephropathy.

3. Arterial Stiffness and Vascular Changes

Inflammation in the blood vessels triggers a series of pathologic changes, such as endothelial dysfunction calcification, vascular growth, and remodeling. These changes, many of which are moderated by angiotensin II, can lead to arterial wall stiffness, which is an independent predictor of CV events in patients with hypertension.

The major evidence for the effects of {{ drug.name }} on vascular stiffness comes from studies of pulse wave velocity ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), also an independent marker of target organ damage. In the Framingham Heart study, each standard deviation increase in carotid-femoral {{ drug.molecular_formula }} was associated with a 48% increase in the adjusted risk of a first major CV event (hazard ratio (HR), 1.48; 95% confidence interval (CI), 1.16–1.91; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 2). Clinical studies show that {{ drug.name }} reduces {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in hypertension, hypertension plus type 2 diabetes, and in hypertension plus chronic kidney disease. Another measure of arterial stiffness is the cardioankle vascular index. In hypertensive patients, 12-month treatment with {{ drug.name }} had beneficial effects on the cardioankle vascular index, as well as on albuminuria, 24-hour {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}, and metabolism compared with calcium channel blockers ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}).

Angiotensin II is also involved in the formation of aneurysms, and {{ drug.name }} has been found to prevent their formation in two animal models. In mice deficient in regulator of G-protein signaling 2 ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}; a negative regulator of AT1 receptors), {{ drug.name }} reduced the incidence of aneurysms. In rat aortic tissue, {{ drug.name }} prevented abdominal aortic aneurysm progression independently of reducing {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}, by inhibition of proteolysis, apoptosis, and inflammation.

Comparative studies on the vascular effects of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} have mainly been conducted in animal models. For example, in a model of stroke-prone hypertensive rats, {{ drug.name }} reduced vascular remodeling to a greater degree than losartan, an effect attributed to reduced {{ drug.molecular_formula }} oxidase activity. In an invitro study, {{ drug.name }} (but not candesartan, irbesartan, or eprosartan) significantly inhibited the proliferation of vascular smooth muscle cells and cardiac fibroblasts in culture when tested at clinically relevant concentrations. At least one comparative human study has been conducted. In Japanese hypertensive patients, {{ drug.name }} provided greater vascular protection than losartan over 1year, as shown by progression of intima-media thickness of common carotid artery, despite similar {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reductions.

4. Insulin Resistance and New-Onset Diabetes

Inflammation and vasoconstriction, and the resulting fibrosis, apoptosis, and pancreatic β-cell death are thought to be the mechanisms that link angiotensin II to metabolic disturbances, such as the development of insulin resistance and new-onset diabetes. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockade improves blood flow and microcirculation in skeletal muscles, which enhances insulin and glucose delivery to the insulin-sensitive tissues, facilitating insulin signaling at the cellular level, and improving insulin secretion by the β cells. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockade would also be expected to reverse the deleterious effects of angiotensin II in the pancreas such as fibrosis, inflammation, apoptosis, and β-cell death.

Numerous clinical trials and meta-analyses have found that while diuretics and β-blockers may worsen insulin resistance and impair glucose tolerance, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockers have the potential for positive metabolic effects. A systematic review of 22 clinical trials involving 143,153 individuals without diabetes showed that the risk of new-onset diabetes was lowest for {{ drug.molecular_formula }} treatment (8.4%; odds ratio (OR), 0.57; 95% CI, 0.46–0.72; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 0 1), followed by {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitors (7.1%; OR, 0.67; 95% CI, 0.56–0.80; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 0 1), {{ drug.molecular_formula }} (7.2%; OR, 0.75; 95% CI, 0.62–0.90; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 2), placebo (6.8%; OR, 0.77; 95% CI, 0.63–0.94; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 9), and β blockers (7.6%; OR, 0.90; 95% CI, 0.75–1.09; 𝑃 = 0 . 3 0).

This reflects the fact that major {{ drug.molecular_formula }} trials generally reduce new-onset diabetes. The relative risk reduction for new-onset diabetes (as a secondary end point) was 25% with losartan versus atenolol in hypertensive patients with {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in the losartan intervention for endpoint reduction in hypertension ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) study (𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 1), 23% with valsartan versus amlodipine in high-risk hypertensive patients in the valsartan antihypertensive long-term use evaluation ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) study (𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 0 1), and 25% with candesartan versus placebo in hypertensive patients in the study on cognition and prognosis in the elderly ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) trial (𝑃 = 0 . 0 9). In the nateglinide and valsartan in impaired glucose tolerance outcomes research ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) trial, valsartan significantly reduced the development of diabetes compared with placebo in patients with impaired glucose tolerance and one or more CV risk factors (if ≥55 years old) or established CV disease (if ≥50 years old) (33.1% versus 36.8%; HR, 0.86; 95% CI, 0.80–0.92; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 1).

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} found {{ drug.name }} to have a similar effect on new-onset diabetes to ramipril ({{ drug.name }} 7.5%, ramipril 6.7%, and dual {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockade 6.1%). However, in the {{ drug.name }} randomised assessment study in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} intolerant subjects with cardiovascular Disease ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), which was a parallel study to {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in 5926 {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitor-intolerant patients, {{ drug.name }} did not reduce the incidence of new-onset diabetes versus placebo (21.8% versus 22.4%; relative risk, 0.95; 95% CI, 0.83–1.10; 𝑃 = 0 . 5 1). On the other hand, a combined analysis of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and the prevention regimen for effectively avoiding second strokes ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) trial did find a significantly reduction in the incidence of new-onset diabetes by 16% compared with placebo.

In addition to the standard effects of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} on angiotensin II-mediated processes, {{ drug.name }} acts as a selective peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ) modulator. Although several {{ drug.molecular_formula }} exhibit this property, there is a clear order of potency, with {{ drug.name }} being the most potent, followed by irbesartan, then losartan. Importantly, {{ drug.name }} is the only {{ drug.molecular_formula }} that may modulate PPARγ activation at physiologic plasma concentrations, an effect that is likely to be related to {{ drug.name }} high lipophilicity. Several studies have found that {{ drug.name }} can influence PPARγ gene expression. In treatment-naïve hypertensive patients, 3-month {{ drug.name }} (but not amlodipine) treatment significantly increased PPARγ mRNA levels (𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 6) in peripheral monocytes, and, in treatment-naïve patients with the metabolic syndrome, high-dose ({{ drug.strength }} once daily) {{ drug.name }} for 14 weeks induced monocytic PPARγ genes. An in vitro study found that {{ drug.name }}, but not candesartan or losartan, upregulated PPARγ expression. However, other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} may also have some clinically meaningful PPARγ activity in one study in humans, treatment with losartan for 2 months increased PPARγ genes versus no treatment in monocytes, probably through the action of the transient losartan aldehyde metabolite, {{ drug.molecular_formula }}.

Numerous in vitro and animal studies have compared the effects of {{ drug.name }} with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockers on metabolic outcomes. {{ drug.name }} or perindopril similarly protected pancreatic islet function in rats fed a high-fat diet; mechanisms included downregulation of islet inflammation, oxidative stress, endoplasmic reticulum stress, and apoptosis. In rats, {{ drug.name }} or irbesartan (not eprosartan) induced adiponectin in adipocytes, and this was associated with improved insulin sensitivity. In an in vitro study, {{ drug.name }}, but not candesartan, increased glucose transporter 4 levels at the plasma membrane. In one study, both {{ drug.name }} and the PPARγ agonist, rosiglitazone, reduced adipose tissue inflammation (measured by markers such as {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-1) and improved insulin resistance and glucose intolerance in a diet-induced obesity mouse model. Similarly, both {{ drug.name }} or rosiglitazone, but not valsartan, ameliorated hyperglycemia and the metabolic profile in diabetic hypertensive rats via PPARγ modulation.

Comparative studies in humans are also common but are generally characterized by small patient numbers. Broadly speaking, however, these studies show that {{ drug.name }} provides greater efficacy than other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. In a randomized, open-label, 24-week study, {{ drug.name }}/rosuvastatin provided favorable effects compared with irbesartan/rosuvastatin or olmesartan/rosuvastatin on glucose metabolism in patients with hypertension, impaired fasting glucose, and dyslipidemia. {{ drug.name }}, but not olmesartan, improved adiponectin levels in hypertensive patients with glucose intolerance. In patients with the metabolic syndrome, {{ drug.name }} improved glucose sensitivity versus losartan, valsartan, and irbesartan. {{ drug.name }} also improved glucose sensitivity versus irbesartan in nondiabetic, obese, and insulin-resistant hypertensive patients. Another study found a benefit with {{ drug.name }} but not olmesartan in overweight/obese hypertensive patients. Several studies have found that replacement of valsartan or candesartan with {{ drug.name }} improved fasting plasma insulin or glucose.

Overall, these studies confirm the beneficial metabolic profile of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and point towards potential differences in the metabolic effects of {{ drug.name }} compared with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. Such differences may be linked to the PPARγ-modulating effects of {{ drug.name }}, or could be a consequence of other pharmacologic differences. However, in the absence of clear evidence of differences in larger trials, the clinical implications of these difference remain uncertain.

5. Albuminuria and Renal Disease

As with other effects on target organ damage, the predominant beyond-{{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} effect of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} on the kidney is related to the reduction of inflammation and oxidative stress although stimulation of the angiotensin II type 2 receptor may also be important to the effects of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} on the kidney.

There is substantial evidence for the efficacy of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in reducing microalbuminuria or slowing the progression to proteinuria and overt nephropathy. Notably, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} have been shown to be superior to {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in the irbesartan diabetic nephropathy trial ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), the microalbuminuria reduction with valsartan ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) study, and the recent Japanese valsartan amlodipine randomized trial ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) study, in which valsartan significantly improved the secondary end point of urinary albumin to creatinine ratio ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) versus amlodipine (–61.3% versus +34.9%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 0 1). The randomized olmesartan and diabetes microalbuminuria prevention ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) study sought to assess whether olmesartan could delay or prevent the occurrence of microalbuminuria in patients with type 2 diabetes and normoalbuminuria. After a median 3.2 years, there was a nonsignificant increase (17%) in the time to onset of microalbuminuria with olmesartan after adjustment for differences in {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reduction. However, this was accompanied by increased CV mortality versus placebo (0.7% versus 0.1%; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 1).

Preclinical models have found that {{ drug.name }} also has direct protective effects on the kidney. In a rat model of glomerulonephritis, high-dose {{ drug.name }} ameliorated glomerular and tubulointerstitial damage. Possible pathways included growth factor signaling, the mammalian target of rapamycin signaling, protein ubiquitination, the Wnt/β catenin pathway, and hypoxia signaling. {{ drug.name }} also reduced the urinary albumin excretion rate ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) and proteinuria to a greater degree than amlodipine in a rat model of aldosterone-induced glomerular injury. In spontaneously hypertensive rats fed with a high-fat diet, {{ drug.name }} was more effective than valsartan in reducing body weight, renal inflammation ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}-1), and renal injury ({{ drug.molecular_formula }} and glomerular damage).

