{{ drug.name }} has been found to exert a greater antiproteinuric effect than losartan. In A {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }} versus losartan {{ drug.strength }} in hypertensive type-2 diabEtic patients with overt nephropathy ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) study, 860 patients with diabetic nephropathy were treated with {{ drug.name }} or losartan for 1 year. Despite matched {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reductions, {{ drug.name }} provided a significantly greater reduction in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} compared with losartan (29.8% versus 21.4%; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 3). In a related study, the trial to investigate the efficacy of {{ drug.name }} versus valsartan in hypertensive type 2 diabetic patients with overt nephropathy ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) found similar reductions in 24-hour {{ drug.molecular_formula }} with {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }} versus valsartan {{ drug.strength }} in 885 patients with hypertension and diabetic nephropathy (33% reduction in both groups, although patients in the valsartan group required additional antihypertensive comedication). However, the inflammatory parameter, urinary excretion of 8-iso-prostaglandin F2α (8-iso-PGF2α), decreased significantly more with {{ drug.name }} versus valsartan (14% versus 7%, 𝑃 = 0 . 0 4 0).

6. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and Cardiac Remodeling

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} is a common form of target organ damage associated with hypertension that increases the risk for CV morbidity and mortality, and, as with other forms of target organ damage, angiotensin II plays a central role in promoting {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} as a class are among the most effective antihypertensives in reducing {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, an effect that is probably due to their interruption of the fibrotic and trophic effects of angiotensin II.

In rat/mouse models of {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, {{ drug.name }} has shown beneficial effects on reducing endoplasmic reticulum stress, apoptosis, and indexes of cardiac hypertrophy. In one study, the development of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in rats was accompanied by changes in the expression of 17 proteins, primarily involved in cell structure, metabolism, stress, and signal transduction. Importantly, these changes were prevented or attenuated by {{ drug.name }} treatment. {{ drug.name }} has also been found to improve left ventricular function significantly and ameliorate the progression of cardiac remodeling in rats with chronic heart failure. Activation of PPARγ-dependent pathways are thought to be involved in development of cardiac hypertrophy, and several studies have investigated whether PPARγ modulation with {{ drug.name }} contributes to its effects on {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. In a rat model of MI, {{ drug.name }} prevented cardiac remodeling by reducing cardiac hypertrophy and fibrosis; this study suggested that the mechanisms involved an anti-inflammatory effect and PPARγ activation in addition to suppression of angiotensin II activity. In diabetic rats, {{ drug.name }} improved ischemia/reperfusion injury, whereas a PPARγ antagonist worsened ischemia/reperfusion injury, suggestive of a role for PPARγ activation. In a hypertensive rat model, both {{ drug.name }} and olmesartan had beneficial effects on cardiac structure and function. As olmesartan has little PPARγ activity, this indicates that the mechanism may be pressor related or AT1 receptor dependent, and other recent research suggests that pioglitazone may not attenuate the development of {{ drug.molecular_formula }}.

{{ drug.name }} is more effective than {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and carvedilol in regressing {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, which supports other evidence that {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockers have particular efficacy on this outcome. Similarly in {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, {{ drug.name }} significantly reduced the risk of developing {{ drug.molecular_formula }} compared with placebo (most patients received non-{{ drug.molecular_formula }}/{{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitor antihypertensive therapy) by 21% overall (OR, 0.79; 95% CI, 0.68–0.91; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 1 7) and by 37% for new-onset {{ drug.molecular_formula }} (OR, 0.63; 95% CI, 0.51–0.79; 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 0 1). Overall, the effects of {{ drug.name }} on {{ drug.molecular_formula }} appear to be similar to those of other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockers. In patients with acute MI, {{ drug.name }} was equivalent to enalapril in suppressing vascular inflammation and reducing {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. In a subgroup analysis of 287 patients who underwent magnetic resonance imaging in {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, {{ drug.name }} was equivalent to ramipril in improving left ventricular mass ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) and volume at 2years. In hypertensive patients, reductions in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} were similar with {{ drug.name }} (11.4%) and ramipril (9.9%), despite similar {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reductions in the groups. One small double-blind study of hypertensive patients (nine with {{ drug.molecular_formula }}) showed that {{ drug.name }} or losartan for 6 months provided similar reductions in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} index and {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}.

7. Atrial Fibrillation

One functional consequence of the effects of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockade on cardiac remodeling may be a reduction in the incidence of atrial fibrillation (AF). For example, in the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} study, 8851 hypertensive patients at risk of AF were followed up for 5 years. New-onset AF was significantly reduced by losartan compared with the β-blocker atenolol (6.8 versus 10.1 per 1000 person-years; relative risk 0.67; 95% CI, 0.55–0.83; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 1), despite similar {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reductions. This hypothesis was supported by two meta-analyses: firstly, 23 randomized, controlled trials (𝑛 = 8 7 , 0 4 8) found that {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitors reduced the OR for primary or secondary AF by 33% (𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 0 0 1). In a second meta-analysis of 11 randomized controlled trials (𝑛 = 5 6 , 3 0 8), the relative risk of primary or secondary AF was reduced by both {{ drug.molecular_formula }} (29%, 𝑃 = 0 . 0 0 0 0 2) and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} inhibitors (28%, 𝑃 = 0 . 0 1).

However, more recent randomized, placebo-controlled studies of valsartan, olmesartan, and irbesartan have been disappointing. Valsartan and placebo were associated with similar rates of recurrent AF over 1 year in patients with previous AF as well as CV disease, diabetes, or left atrial enlargement (51.4% versus 52.1%; adjusted HR, 0.97; 96% CI, 0.83–1.14; 𝑃 = 0 . 7 3). Olmesartan and placebo groups had similar rates of AF burden (percentage of days with paroxysmal AF) over 12 months in a study of patients with documented paroxysmal AF without structural heart disease. In high-risk patients with AF, for 4 years irbesartan and placebo were associated with similar rates of composite CV outcome (risk of stroke, MI, or death from vascular causes) (5.4% versus 5.4% per 100 person-years; HR, 0.99; 95% CI, 0.91–1.08; 𝑃 = 0 . 8 5) or this composite outcome plus hospitalization for heart failure (7.3% versus 7.7% per 100 person-years; HR, 0.94; 95% CI, 0.87–1.02; 𝑃 = 0 . 1 2).

In contrast to recent studies with other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, clinical trials with {{ drug.name }} have shown reductions in the incidence of AF. In the high-CV-risk patients in {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, {{ drug.name }} was as effective as ramipril on the end point of new-onset AF (with an incidence of 6.7% versus 6.9%, resp.). In hypertensive patients with the metabolic syndrome and a history of AF, {{ drug.name }} was more effective than ramipril in reducing the recurrence of AF over 1year (12.9% versus 25.5%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 5) as well as the severity of AF, despite a similar {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reduction. In patients with hypertension and a history of AF, {{ drug.name }} was associated with a significantly lower rate of new episodes of AF compared with the β blocker, carvedilol (14.3% versus 37.1%; 𝑃 < 0 . 0 0 3), again despite a similar {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reduction.

8. Cerebrovascular Disease

Angiotensin II may contribute to the pathogenesis of stroke. Recently, in stroke-prone spontaneously hypertensive rats, {{ drug.name }}, ramipril, and the combination had similar beneficial effects on stroke incidence. However, {{ drug.name }} and {{ drug.name }}/ramipril provided superior neuroprotection compared with ramipril alone in normotensive rats with induced cerebral ischemia, as shown by improved nitric oxide, reduced infarct volume, and inflammation (TNFα), and induced neurotrophin receptor and neuronal survival. In the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} trial in 20,332 patients, {{ drug.name }} initiated soon after an ischemic stroke did not significantly reduce the rate of recurrent stroke, major CV events, or new-onset diabetes compared with standard care over a 2.5-year period .However, in a post-hoc exploratory analysis, the rate of recurrent stroke was lower with {{ drug.name }} compared with standard care after 6 months (5.3% versus 6.0%; HR, 0.88; 95% CI, 0.78–0.99)

Antihypertensive medications may reduce the incidence of Alzheimer’s disease. In a randomized study of elderly hypertensive patients with probable Alzheimer’s disease, 6-month treatment with {{ drug.name }} reduced cognitive decline compared with amlodipine Cognitive function test scores were unchanged in the {{ drug.name }} group and significantly higher in the amlodipine group. In addition, {{ drug.name }} increased cerebral blood flow in the right supramarginal gyrus, superior parietal lobule, cuneus, and lingual gyrus compared with amlodipine, while amlodipine increased cerebral blood flow only in the right cingulate gyrus compared with {{ drug.name }}.

9. Conclusions

The {{ drug.molecular_formula }} trial was a landmark for clinical practice, proving for the first time that an {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, {{ drug.name }}, could prevent CV events in high-CV-risk patients to a degree similar to ramipril. Since CV disease occurs as a progressive continuum, such effects on CV outcomes imply an effect on the underlying disease pathology as well as intermediate end points, such as target organ damage. This review has sought to investigate the evidence for {{ drug.name }}’s effects on these CV disease processes, with a view to assisting in interpretation of the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} trial results.

There is substantial evidence, reviewed here, that blockade of the angiotensin II receptor by {{ drug.name }} has a direct and beneficial effect of key aspects of CV disease. In common with other blockers of the {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, {{ drug.name }} has been shown to reduce inflammation and oxidative stress, which is the most important process linking the direct effect of angiotensin II to CV disease progression. This likely explains the effects observed on vascular wall stiffness and downstream effects on target organ damage, such as reduced albuminuria and renal dysfunction, reduced {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, and reduced risk of AF. {{ drug.name }} also improves metabolic parameters, an effect that may be due to {{ drug.molecular_formula }} blockade but which may also be related to {{ drug.name }}’s ability to modulate PPARγ.

The extent to which pharmacologic differences between {{ drug.molecular_formula }} translate into clinically meaningful effects is difficult to confirm, but, on the evidence reviewed here, {{ drug.name }} may have superior effects over certain other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}—with the strongest evidence being the superiority of {{ drug.name }} over losartan on the reduction in proteinuria in the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} study. Since proteinuria is a strong indicator of CV risk, it seems reasonable to expect that differential effects between these two drugs on CV outcomes are likely.

In summary, the prevention of CV events with {{ drug.name }} observed in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} is likely to be a consequence of the direct effects of {{ drug.name }} on CV disease pathology, notably effects on inflammation and target organ damage. Differences exist between {{ drug.molecular_formula }} on these intermediate end points, which reflect differences in their pharmacology. Whether other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} have effects similar to {{ drug.name }} on CV outcomes remains to be tested.

